00:05:21.980 --> 00:05:28.080
So let's start with a somewhat
detailed introduction to what

00:05:28.080 --> 00:05:34.030
it is that Cass Sunstein said
in the 1996 article that we

00:05:34.030 --> 00:05:38.500
read for last Tuesday's class.

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:43.470
What Sunstein is attempting
to do in that piece is to

00:05:43.470 --> 00:05:49.150
identify the ways in which our
attitudes towards certain

00:05:49.150 --> 00:05:54.230
kinds of behaviors on our part
and the part of others towards

00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:57.430
certain sorts of decisions on
our part and the part of

00:05:57.430 --> 00:06:03.800
others are affected by what he
calls, drawing from a large

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:08.110
body of sociological literature,
social norms.

00:06:08.110 --> 00:06:12.710
Social norms are basically
social attitudes of approval

00:06:12.710 --> 00:06:18.040
and disapproval that specify,
through the kinds of tacit

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:24.130
mechanisms that human beings
as social primates have for

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:27.990
expressing disapproval
and approval of

00:06:27.990 --> 00:06:31.720
one's and other's actions.

00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:36.000
That is, social attitudes of
approval and disapproval

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.070
specifying what ought
to be done and what

00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:41.110
ought not to be done.

00:06:41.110 --> 00:06:45.820
Subtle things like nuanced
facial expressions,

00:06:45.820 --> 00:06:50.880
approaches, avoidances, all of
the social cues to which we

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:55.150
are extraordinarily sensitive
in infancy, to which we are

00:06:55.150 --> 00:07:00.202
extraordinarily sensitive in our
early years, to which we

00:07:00.202 --> 00:07:05.520
are absolutely, exquisitely
sensitive in middle school and

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:06.750
high school.

00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:11.680
And to which we continue to be
sensitive throughout our life.

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:15.870
What Sunstein points out is that
social norms determine

00:07:15.870 --> 00:07:16.930
social meanings.

00:07:16.930 --> 00:07:20.420
That is, they determine the
attitudes and commitments that

00:07:20.420 --> 00:07:24.750
a particular type of
conduct signals.

00:07:24.750 --> 00:07:30.860
So, he points out, if you fasten
your seatbelt in a

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:38.270
country where seatbelt use is
not the norm then you express

00:07:38.270 --> 00:07:46.330
in so doing implicit criticism
of the ability of your driver

00:07:46.330 --> 00:07:50.320
to navigate the car effectively
on the highway.

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:54.539
Fastening your seatbelt
is an insult.

00:07:54.539 --> 00:07:59.250
When my family and I rent cars
in Eastern Europe, where my

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:03.270
husband is from, rental cars
typically come, if you don't

00:08:03.270 --> 00:08:08.840
rent them from a major agency,
with a small metal plate that

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:12.670
you can slide into the seatbelt
lock without having a

00:08:12.670 --> 00:08:16.250
seatbelt attached to it so
that the annoying beeping

00:08:16.250 --> 00:08:19.230
sound goes off and you
don't have to wear

00:08:19.230 --> 00:08:22.640
your insulting seatbelt.

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:28.300
Whereas in nations where
seatbelt use is the norm,

00:08:28.300 --> 00:08:33.690
where seatbelt use is in fact
the law, the failure to fasten

00:08:33.690 --> 00:08:39.330
your seatbelt is an expression
of disrespect.

00:08:39.330 --> 00:08:43.590
When I was growing up my
family, to my great

00:08:43.590 --> 00:08:48.650
embarrassment, separated its
vegetable scraps from its

00:08:48.650 --> 00:08:51.600
paper scraps and put them
in the backyard

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:54.910
into a compost heap.

00:08:54.910 --> 00:09:00.250
The social meaning of a compost
heap in the 1970s in

00:09:00.250 --> 00:09:07.460
suburban Massachusetts was
one of non-normativity.

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:13.880
It was one of an expression,
perhaps, that we were more

00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:17.770
socially conscious than our
neighbors, perhaps thought we

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:19.890
were better than
our neighbors.

00:09:19.890 --> 00:09:25.320
But whatever it was it wasn't
a way of fitting in.

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:29.750
It is now the case in large
portions of America that a

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:34.460
compost heap or the carrying
of a recyclable bag or the

00:09:34.460 --> 00:09:39.170
replacement of your light bulb
with a full-spectrum long-term

00:09:39.170 --> 00:09:44.370
bulb simply expresses respect
for the environment rather

00:09:44.370 --> 00:09:47.810
than an outlier attitude.

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:51.300
My Hungarian nephew, when he
came to visit us this summer,

00:09:51.300 --> 00:09:57.640
wore what he thought to be
very stylish Iron Maiden

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:03.110
t-shirts, which in Budapest were
in expression of cool.

00:10:03.110 --> 00:10:09.170
In our suburban Connecticut
environment, his actions were

00:10:09.170 --> 00:10:14.230
often misperceived as rebellious
because of the

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:18.780
social signals that
his clothing sent.

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:23.420
So the reason that I had you
read the Sunstein article in

00:10:23.420 --> 00:10:27.670
the context of our political
philosophy discussion was to

00:10:27.670 --> 00:10:35.030
point out to you how many more
layers of complexity there are

00:10:35.030 --> 00:10:39.950
when we start thinking about
what kind of social structures

00:10:39.950 --> 00:10:42.920
are legitimate.

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:47.250
There was, in addition, a very
particular question about the

00:10:47.250 --> 00:10:51.180
Sunstein article, which was
raised in the context of our

00:10:51.180 --> 00:10:55.930
feedback page, about which I
want to say a small bit by way

00:10:55.930 --> 00:10:57.730
of transition.

00:10:57.730 --> 00:11:02.120
So one of the students asked
whether I could characterize

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:05.890
Sunstein's somewhat complicated
argument about

00:11:05.890 --> 00:11:09.390
willingness to pay and
willingness to allow.

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:11.640
So what we're doing now is
we're looking at a very

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:16.440
particular girder of a very
particular argument.

00:11:16.440 --> 00:11:21.760
So Sunstein in that article, you
may recall, introduces a

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:26.480
discussion of what's known as
the endowment effect, which is

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:31.730
basically the tendency of human
beings to demand more to

00:11:31.730 --> 00:11:36.510
give up an owned object then
they would be prepared to pay

00:11:36.510 --> 00:11:39.720
to acquire that object.

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:44.120
And the term for how much it is
that somebody's willing to

00:11:44.120 --> 00:11:51.300
sell something for is WTA,
willingness to accept payment,

00:11:51.300 --> 00:11:54.040
whereas the term for that which
somebody's willing to

00:11:54.040 --> 00:12:00.400
pay for an object is WTP,
or willingness to pay.

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:08.290
It turns out that if I have a
beautiful Yale mug, which I

00:12:08.290 --> 00:12:16.090
seek to sell to you, that our
assessments of its value will

00:12:16.090 --> 00:12:18.720
very often differ.

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:22.990
I may well say that I won't part
with my beautiful mug for

00:12:22.990 --> 00:12:25.350
anything less than $10.

00:12:25.350 --> 00:12:29.610
Whereas you say, "I wouldn't
buy your crappy old mug for

00:12:29.610 --> 00:12:34.610
anything more than $5." Even
if, when we alter the

00:12:34.610 --> 00:12:38.610
situation and you have the
mug and I don't, our

00:12:38.610 --> 00:12:41.800
responses are inverted.

00:12:41.800 --> 00:12:45.320
I wouldn't buy your crappy old
mug for anything more than $5

00:12:45.320 --> 00:12:48.950
and you wouldn't part with it
for anything less than $10.

00:12:48.950 --> 00:12:54.830
Now Sunstein, 15 years ago in
this article, hypothesizes

00:12:54.830 --> 00:13:00.440
that what explains this effect
is primarily something about

00:13:00.440 --> 00:13:06.520
social norms. It looks like, at
least to some extent, that

00:13:06.520 --> 00:13:08.850
he was wrong about that.

00:13:08.850 --> 00:13:12.350
At least that he was wrong
that social norms fully

00:13:12.350 --> 00:13:14.670
explain the phenomena.

00:13:14.670 --> 00:13:18.810
Because research done in Laurie
Santos lab at this very

00:13:18.810 --> 00:13:24.380
university in the last five
years seems to suggest that

00:13:24.380 --> 00:13:28.490
something akin to the endowment
effect can be found

00:13:28.490 --> 00:13:31.660
even in Capuchin monkeys.

00:13:31.660 --> 00:13:38.380
A tendency to value more that
which is yours than that which

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:43.650
is not, even when the objects
are identical.

00:13:43.650 --> 00:13:49.590
That said, there is still reason
to think that Sunstein

00:13:49.590 --> 00:13:54.950
is on to something when he
argues that the willingness to

00:13:54.950 --> 00:14:00.680
pay, willingness to allow
distinction, in some ways is

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:04.720
tracking something about
social meaning.

00:14:04.720 --> 00:14:10.460
So he points out that in a
series of studies done in the

00:14:10.460 --> 00:14:16.570
context of behavioral economics
with WEIRD subjects

00:14:16.570 --> 00:14:21.660
near the University of Chicago,
for at least Western,

00:14:21.660 --> 00:14:26.850
educated, industrialized, rich,
democratic, adults, it

00:14:26.850 --> 00:14:32.240
looks like this asymmetry
is rather profound.

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:36.150
So he described this study,
the details of which I had

00:14:36.150 --> 00:14:40.760
thought I would go through but I
won't, in which what you see

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:46.550
is a rather radical asymmetry
in subject's willingness to

00:14:46.550 --> 00:14:51.730
either acquire an object from
another or part with an object

00:14:51.730 --> 00:14:54.200
that they own.

00:14:54.200 --> 00:14:58.050
Sunstein's response to these
sorts of cases is to suggest

00:14:58.050 --> 00:15:01.470
that the difference here has a
lot to do with social norms

00:15:01.470 --> 00:15:03.270
and meanings.

00:15:03.270 --> 00:15:08.730
So that being willing to, for
example accept a certain

00:15:08.730 --> 00:15:14.730
amount of money to allow the
extinction of a species has a

00:15:14.730 --> 00:15:18.460
very different social
meaning than--

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:21.860
what you might think of as
structurally the same--

00:15:21.860 --> 00:15:26.710
accepting, or being willing to
pay a certain amount of money

00:15:26.710 --> 00:15:30.570
to prevent the extinction
of the species.

00:15:30.570 --> 00:15:36.450
Whether you consider the state
of the world where the species

00:15:36.450 --> 00:15:40.980
is extinct or whether you
consider the state of the

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:45.340
world where the species is
present and it's your job to

00:15:45.340 --> 00:15:50.840
save it, to be the baseline,
turns out to affect people's

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:52.890
evaluation of it.

00:15:52.890 --> 00:15:57.120
And Sunstein suggests in the
article, more generally, that

00:15:57.120 --> 00:16:01.430
numerous of our actions,
numerous of our decisions, are

00:16:01.430 --> 00:16:05.180
driven at least in part
by internal and

00:16:05.180 --> 00:16:08.086
external social meaning.

00:16:08.086 --> 00:16:13.030
And that, as a consequence,
an effective mechanism for

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:17.970
influencing actions and
decisions is to influence the

00:16:17.970 --> 00:16:21.320
social meanings of those
actions and decisions.

00:16:21.320 --> 00:16:27.944
So that, he suggests, it turns
out to be an inevitable role

00:16:27.944 --> 00:16:37.210
of government to regulate
behavior by the affirmation or

00:16:37.210 --> 00:16:40.670
introduction or disavowal
of certain

00:16:40.670 --> 00:16:43.560
kinds of social meaning.

00:16:43.560 --> 00:16:48.660
And we address the issue of
this sort of indirect

00:16:48.660 --> 00:16:53.240
non-rational control of behavior
in the context of our

00:16:53.240 --> 00:16:56.880
discussion of Plato
on censorship.

00:16:56.880 --> 00:17:00.590
Now this distinction between
willingness to pay and

00:17:00.590 --> 00:17:04.090
willingness to allow, the
details of which we're now

00:17:04.090 --> 00:17:09.670
going to set aside, can be used
to think about one of the

00:17:09.670 --> 00:17:13.320
examples, which we talked about
in many lectures and

00:17:13.320 --> 00:17:16.660
which we'll talk about
again on Thursday.

00:17:16.660 --> 00:17:22.410
Namely, the fact that there is
an undeniable tendency of

00:17:22.410 --> 00:17:28.860
people, this class included, to
respond differently to the

00:17:28.860 --> 00:17:33.222
classic trolley case, where one
diverts a trolley from a

00:17:33.222 --> 00:17:36.810
track where it's about to hit
five onto a track where it's

00:17:36.810 --> 00:17:42.390
about to hit one, and trolley
cases involving pushing

00:17:42.390 --> 00:17:45.700
someone off a bridge.

00:17:45.700 --> 00:17:52.650
So whereas the first one among
you produced only 15% of you

00:17:52.650 --> 00:17:56.830
saying that it was prohibited
to turn the trolley, the

00:17:56.830 --> 00:17:59.840
second case, the one where
you're asked to push the fat

00:17:59.840 --> 00:18:05.050
man off the bridge, thereby
killing one and saving five,

00:18:05.050 --> 00:18:10.770
